<Layout title="Pediatric Assessment Tools" description="Pediatric assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Pediatric</div>
  <h1>Pediatric Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Age-appropriate clinical tools for pediatric early warning, illness severity, developmental screening, and behavioral assessment.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pediatric GCS (Glasgow Coma Scale)</strong> — Age-modified GCS with developmentally appropriate verbal response categories for infants and young children who cannot produce adult verbal responses.</li>
      <li><strong>PEWS (Pediatric Early Warning Score)</strong> — Behavioral, cardiovascular, and respiratory domain scoring to identify children at risk for deterioration; triggers escalation protocols.</li>
      <li><strong>Pediatric SOFA</strong> — Age-appropriate organ failure assessment adapted from adult SOFA with pediatric reference ranges for respiratory, coagulation, liver, cardiovascular, neurological, and renal systems.</li>
      <li><strong>PRISM III (Pediatric Risk of Mortality)</strong> — 17-variable physiologic score predicting PICU mortality; replaces original PRISM and includes cardiovascular, neurological, acid-base, and biochemistry variables.</li>
      <li><strong>PIM3 (Pediatric Index of Mortality 3)</strong> — Eight-variable PICU admission severity score predicting mortality probability; validated internationally for benchmarking.</li>
      <li><strong>PELOD-2 (Pediatric Logistic Organ Dysfunction)</strong> — Six-organ pediatric organ dysfunction scoring: neurological, cardiovascular, renal, respiratory, hematological, hepatic; total score 0–33.</li>
      <li><strong>Broselow Tape</strong> — Length-based pediatric weight estimation and color-coded medication dosing reference; standard of care for rapid pediatric emergency dosing when weight is unknown.</li>
      <li><strong>FLACC Scale</strong> — Pain assessment for non-verbal children and infants: Face, Legs, Activity, Cry, Consolability; scores 0–2 each for total 0–10.</li>
      <li><strong>Faces Pain Scale-Revised (FPS-R)</strong> — Six-face self-report pain scale validated for children ages 4–12 years; no smiling face used to avoid conflation of happiness with pain absence.</li>
      <li><strong>COMFORT Scale</strong> — Pediatric ICU pain and sedation assessment: alertness, calmness/agitation, respiratory distress, movement, facial tension, and muscle tone (6–30 total).</li>
      <li><strong>CARS (Childhood Autism Rating Scale)</strong> — 15-item observational rating scale for autism spectrum disorder diagnosis; score ≥30 indicates autism; ≥37 severe autism.</li>
      <li><strong>M-CHAT (Modified Checklist for Autism in Toddlers)</strong> — 20-item parent-report autism screening for children 16–30 months; positive screen triggers follow-up interview and referral.</li>
      <li><strong>ASQ (Ages and Stages Questionnaire)</strong> — Age-specific developmental screening questionnaire for communication, gross motor, fine motor, problem solving, and personal-social domains; completed by parents.</li>
      <li><strong>PSC (Pediatric Symptom Checklist)</strong> — 35-item parent-completed psychosocial screening for children 4–16 years; identifies emotional and behavioral problems requiring mental health evaluation.</li>
      <li><strong>HEADSS Assessment</strong> — Adolescent psychosocial health framework: Home, Education/Employment, Activities, Drugs, Sexuality, Suicide/Self-harm. Structured confidential interview for adolescent preventive care.</li>
      <li><strong>Tanner Staging (Sexual Maturity Rating)</strong> — Five-stage assessment of pubertal development (breast/genital development and pubic hair) used for growth monitoring and age-appropriate care planning.</li>
      <li><strong>Growth Chart Percentile Plotting</strong> — CDC and WHO growth charts tracking weight, height, head circumference, and BMI percentiles; identifies failure to thrive, overweight, and growth abnormalities.</li>
      <li><strong>DDST (Denver Developmental Screening Test II)</strong> — Developmental milestone screening for children birth to 6 years across personal-social, fine motor-adaptive, language, and gross motor domains.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
